<br>
I must say that the original poster obviously has no clue about the pressure that you are put under as an FFA raid leader.  Guild raids can sometimes be bad but FFA ones are worse.  <br>
<br>
Why worse ? well you have to keep an eye on EVERYONE to ensure that they are not taking the complete pi*s.  It the none too distant past, I fell out with a gnome warrior I knew during an FFA raid because he was being a loot whore. <br>
<br>
He logged in when we were killing Kiras, he logged out when they were dead, he logged in when we were just about to kill Mae and logged out afterwards.  He got penalised heavily by me for it too.  <br>
<br>
Trouble is as well is that people invite everyone and their dogs, so you have to monitor everything as well as co-ordinate the kill and the loots as well.  <br>
<br>
Raid leaders specifically on FFA have to co-ordinate the loots in order than effort = reward.  <br>
<br>
On my final bow out of FFA (in total) raids in PoH, I pulled, organised the gruops, did the loots, dealt with issues. dealt with invites and prioritised people.  <br>
<br>
Out of a series of raids Thraldor got a full set of Indo and hand of maestro, but tbh he put in far more effort than anyone else.  <br>
<br>
So in conclusion, do not castrate others attempts are raid leadership until you have done plenty of FFA and guildraids to know what is involved and the amount of pressure to deliver you are put under.  <br>
<br>
Whilst you may have been suggesting ways to improve and divide loots fairly, do you not think that maybe you were not the only one ? <br>
<br>
As a raid leader, you can guarantee that you will be taking more than one tell off more than one individual.  <br>
<br>
In fact, during one raid all I did was take tells throughout the whole night and dish out orders.<br>
<br>
And on a final note, raid leaders (IMHO) are empowered to change the loot rules as and when in order that it fits in with the structure of the raid.  This allows them to be more flexible with people who have put in the time and effort, as well as identifying those that are just there to get as much as they can.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raluvinssteele>Raluvin Ssteele</A> at: 1/6/03 9:58:30 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=impudent>impudent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Uber guild basher <br><font color=blue>QC Supporter</span><br>  Posts: 459<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/6/03 11:18:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=763.topic&index=70>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cheatch Learn to run a raid.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And on a final note, raid leaders (IMHO) are empowered to change the loot rules as and when in order that it fits in with the structure of the raid. This allows them to be more flexible with people who have put in the time and effort, as well as identifying those that are just there to get as much as they can. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
